[[File:W54 Special (CA-San Ysidro) -vector.svg|thumb|right|The sign]]

The '''immigration sign''' was a [[United States Numbered Highways|U.S. highway]] [[Road traffic safety|safety sign]] warning motorists to avoid [[Immigration to the United States|immigrants]] darting across the road. It depicted a man, woman, and child with pigtails running. The signs were erected in response to over one hundred immigrant pedestrian deaths due to traffic collisions from 1987 to 1990 in two corridors along [[Interstate 5 in California|Interstate 5]] along the [[San Ysidro Port of Entry]] at the [[Mexico–United States border]] and approximately {{convert |50|mi|km|0}} north at the [[San Clemente, California|San Clemente]] [[United States Border Patrol]] [[United States Border Patrol interior checkpoints|checkpoint]] in [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton|Camp Pendleton]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/01/07/us/one-last-deadly-crossing-for-illegal-aliens.html |title=One Last Deadly Crossing for Illegal Aliens |author=Mydans, Seth |date=7 January 1991 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>

==History==
Immigrant smugglers adopted the tactic of dropping off their human cargo on the shoulder or median of the freeway prior to passing through the checkpoint. Once past the checkpoint, the smugglers would wait for the immigrants to rejoin before proceeding to the final destination. However, in order to avoid the checkpoint (straddling the northbound lanes of the freeway), the immigrants would have to cross the freeway to the southbound shoulder. At the Camp Pendleton checkpoint, immigrants were precluded from passing the checkpoint on the northbound shoulder by rugged terrain and random Marine patrols.<ref name=NYT /> The running family silhouette supplemented all-text signs advising drivers "CAUTION WATCH FOR PEOPLE CROSSING ROAD".<ref name= NYT />

[[File:Caltrans CAUTION PEOPLE CROSSING.svg |thumb|right|All-text sign.]]
The running family silhouette signs were erected starting in September 1990,<ref name= SDUT /> and it is not known how effective they were in reducing traffic strike fatalities before the implementation of other physical measures. Eventually, Caltrans built a tall fence in the I-5 median south of the San Clemente checkpoint, which effectively precluded the checkpoint-avoidance traffic-crossing tactic at Camp Pendleton,<ref name= SDUT /> and the Border Patrol implemented [[Operation Gatekeeper]] in 1995, which erected a tall fence along the San Diego–Tijuana border, moving illegal immigration attempts further east into the desert.<ref name= SDUT />

As of 2008 and later confirmed in July 2017, one sign remained in California,<ref name=ICT-081012>{{cite web |url=https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/iconic-sign-evokes-connection-to-long-walk/ |title=Iconic sign evokes connection to Long Walk |author=Morales, Victor |date=12 October 2008 |publisher=Indian Country Today |accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref> and there are no plans to replace it as it is largely obsolete. The number of people apprehended while illegally crossing the border in the region has seen a 95% decline over thirty years, going from 628,000 arrested in 1986 to 31,891 in 2016.<ref name="LATimes_20170707">{{cite news |title=With only one left, iconic yellow road sign showing running immigrants now borders on the extinct |author=Carcamo, Cindy |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-immigrants-running-road-sign-20170614-htmlstory.html |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=8 July 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708231207/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-immigrants-running-road-sign-20170614-htmlstory.html |archivedate=7 July 2017 |date=7 July 2017 |deadurl=no}}</ref> As of February 2018, the last sign had disappeared.<ref>http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-immigration-sign-20180210-story.html</ref>

==Design and reuse==
[[California Department of Transportation|Caltrans]] graphic artist John Hood, a [[Navajo people|Navajo]] [[Vietnam veteran|Vietnam War veteran]], created the image as an assignment in response to the sharp rise in immigrant traffic deaths.<ref name=LAT>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-outthere4apr04-story.html#page=1 |title=The artist behind the iconic 'running immigrants' image |author=Gold, Scott |date=4 April 2008 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> The image was developed to elicit immediate recognition of the potential traffic hazard and to illustrate the potential running motion with the little girl's flowing pigtails.<ref name=LAT /> The final design process took approximately a week, and Hood drew inspiration from both his experiences in Vietnam as well as stories from his Navajo parents.<ref name=SDUT /> Hood has stated the man's profile is similar to [[Cesar Chavez]], and the child was depicted as a little girl being dragged along because "little girls are dear to the heart, especially for fathers."<ref name=ICT-081012 /> Hood likened the immigrants' plight to the [[Long Walk of the Navajo]] to their present-day reservation in northeastern New Mexico in 1864.<ref name=ICT-081012 />

{{quote|text=It was troublesome that there was a mass exodus, especially families. And when you talk about families, you talk about children. They were getting slaughtered in the freeways. The children don't know what's happening and why they are there. [And] why their parents are doing it. They just know this is not their home. The sign conveys that they are away from home. And the children are asking, 'What are we running for?' Today, even when I watch parents walking in malls with their kids, it's like they are dragging them. That was the idea: clutching something that is dear to our heart. |author=John Hood, Caltrans graphic artist |source=Interview with Victor Morales<ref name=ICT-081012 />}}

Since its deployment it has become a [[popular culture|pop culture]] icon as it appeared on T-shirts and [[anti-immigration]] advertisements in various incarnations.<ref name=SDUT>{{cite news |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20050410/news_1n10signs.html |title=Highway safety sign becomes running story on immigration |author=Berestein, Leslie |date=10 April 2005 |newspaper=San Diego Union-Tribune |accessdate=15 June 2015 }}</ref> It was exhibited in the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s permanent exhibition on transportation,<ref name=SDUT /> and British street artist [[Banksy]] used a modified version of the silhouette family in his ''Kite-2'' artwork exhibited on Los Angeles-area streets in early 2011.<ref name=COLOR>{{cite news |url=http://www.colorlines.com/articles/banksy-transforms-migrant-road-sign-dream-crossing |title=Banksy Transforms Migrant Road Sign into DREAM Crossing |author=Rivas, Jorge |date=22 February 2011 |newspaper=COLORLINES |accessdate=15 June 2015 }}</ref> The silhouette family is also a popular target of parody, spawning variants including ones where the family is depicted wearing caps and gowns (referencing the [[DREAM Act]]); as Joseph, Mary and Jesus;<ref name=SCPR>{{cite web |url=http://www.scpr.org/blogs/multiamerican/2011/03/05/7328/before-banksy-the-running-family-was-immigration-i |title=Before Banksy, the running family was immigration icon and art |author=Berestein Rojas, Leslie |date=5 March 2011 |publisher=89.3 KPCC |accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> as a beer label;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/03/how-i-know-i-am-back-home-in-socal/274398/ |title=How I Know I Am Back Home in SoCal |author=Fallows, James |date=27 March 2013 |newspaper=The Atlantic |accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref> and one where they are wearing Pilgrim gear.<ref name=SDUT /> In June 2018, political cartoonist [[Rob Rogers (cartoonist)|Rob Rogers]] was fired from the [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] after submitting a series of cartoons critical of President Donald Trump, one of which depicted a version of the caution sign with the trailing child being torn away by a silhouetted Trump.<ref name=WAPO>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/comic-riffs/wp/2018/06/14/pittsburgh-post-gazette-fires-anti-trump-cartoonist-and-mayor-says-it-sends-wrong-message-about-press-freedoms/ |title=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette fires anti-Trump cartoonist |author=Cavna, Michael |date=14 June 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>

